title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson Model 1903 .32 Long, made 1910-1917
location: northwest suburbs of Chicago, Chicago, Illinois
postcontent:
Remember Bad, Bad Leroy Brown?  He lived in the baddest part of town and kept a thirty-two gun in his pocket for fun.  Well with its pearl grips and nickel plating, this would have been a thirty-two gun to LeRoy's taste.

This is a .32 Hand Ejector Model of 1903 Fourth Change made between 1910 and 1917, just in advance of the Roarin' Twenties.   It has a 3-1/4 inch barrel, the shortest barrel in the Standard Catalog of Smith & Wesson for this model, so it would have made an appropriate pocket gun.  

I'm not a dealer, just a dedicated collector and this gun was part of a multi-gun lot I acquired early last year.  It really doesn't fit my collection, so I'm trying to find it a new home.   The good news is that the gun works perfectly.  I've put a couple boxes of .32 long through it and it is spot-on accurate and works well in single and double action.  The less good news is that the nickel finish isn't quite pristine, and the price reflects both the guns utility and the current finish.   

When I first handled the gun I thought it was a candidate for rebluing.  Only after removing the grips did I realize it was plated and had spots of tarnish or oxidation as if the gun had spent decades in a glove box.  I carefully cleaned the gun and the solvent removed a lot of lint and soot from the inside of the gun (LeRoy had dirty pockets!).   

After a few applications of Simichrome polish the spots reduced in size, but haven't gone away completely.  While the finish needs work, the bore/lands/grooves are just fine.  Perhaps the new owner can further brighten the finish or enjoy the gun now as a novel backup and treat it as a candidate for future restoration.

Face to face sale is not possible, but I’ll pack/insure/ship for the lower 48 for $22.  Personal check is fine, and I’ll need a SIGNED copy of an FFL or (or C&R license where allowed) and ship to the address on the license.  

Questions?  Call me 9 a.m. to 9 p.m.  Central Time at REDACTED or shoot me an email at REDACTED
